In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `Application` class and use a custom `Window`:

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new AppShell());

    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Or** subclass `Window` and override the methods directly:

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }
    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }
}
```

**Key mapping:**
| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` / `Created` |
| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` / `Stopped` |
| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `Resumed` |

MAUI also adds `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, `OnBackgrounding`, and `OnDestroying` for more granular control.
